"1533","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","about 1446":"circa 1446","1485":"1485","about 1478":"circa 1478","about 1485":"circa 1485","1418":"1418","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England","Wolverton,Buckinghamshire,England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"en":{"about 1446–1489":"about 1446–1489","1446–1489":"1446–1489","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1473–Male":"1473–Deceased","1478–1558":"1478–1558","1480–1558":"1480–1558","1480–1571":"1480–1571","1485–Male":"1485–Deceased","1500–1533":"1500–1533","1414–1459":"1414–1459","1418–1500":"1418–1500","1473":"1473","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1459":"1459","1558":"1558","1414":"1414","1446":"1446","1489":"1489","1533":"1533","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","about 1446":"about 1446","1485":"1485","about 1478":"about 1478","about 1485":"about 1485","1418":"1418","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England","Wolverton,Buckinghamshire,England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jenkes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): patronymic, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from a pet form of the personal names <i>Jukel</i>, <i>Jokel</i>, which are from Breton <i>Judicael</i> and this one from Old Breton <i>Iudicael</i>. The Breton personal name is derived from <i>iuth</i> ‘lord’ with a suffix <i>-ig</i> + <i>hael</i>, <i>hail</i> ‘generous, bountiful’. In England the personal name was particularly common in Yorkshire and Lincolnshire and in districts where Bretons settled after the Norman Conquest. Compare   Jewell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jewell","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall): from an Old Breton personal name, <i>Iudhael</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘lord’ + ‘generous, bountiful’ (see   Jewkes  ), which was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, a king of Brittany who abdicated and spent the last part of his life in a monastery. Forms of this name are found in medieval records not only in Devon and Cornwall, where they are of native origin, but also in East Anglia and even Yorkshire, where they were imported by Bretons after the Norman Conquest. The name was seemingly reintroduced from France in the 17th century by Huguenots."]},{"name":"Jukes","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Jewkes  ."]}]},{"name":"Roland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowland","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":9,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-